1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:01,900
Ten for ten.

2
00:00:01,850 --> 00:00:03,925
Perfect scorecard.

3
00:00:03,925 --> 00:00:06,775
Every sub-agent passed every check.

4
00:00:06,775 --> 00:00:08,412
Git clean.

5
00:00:08,412 --> 00:00:10,175
Code pushed.

6
00:00:10,175 --> 00:00:12,337
Service responding.

7
00:00:12,337 --> 00:00:16,150
The three failures that actually cost us hours this week?

8
00:00:16,150 --> 00:00:18,512
The script caught none of them.

9
00:00:18,512 --> 00:00:20,162
I'm Jake.

10
00:00:20,162 --> 00:00:22,550
This is Jake's Daily Build.

11
00:00:22,550 --> 00:00:24,300
What we built.

12
00:00:24,300 --> 00:00:25,950
What broke.

13
00:00:25,950 --> 00:00:27,800
What I learned.

14
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:34,487
When you delegate work to AI sub-agents, there's a gap between "I asked it to do something" and "it actually did it right.

15
00:00:34,487 --> 00:00:36,675
The agent says done.

16
00:00:36,675 --> 00:00:38,275
Done how?

17
00:00:38,275 --> 00:00:40,075
Did it commit?

18
00:00:40,075 --> 00:00:41,812
Did it push?

19
00:00:41,812 --> 00:00:44,512
Did it break something that was working?

20
00:00:44,512 --> 00:00:47,225
We built a verification script.

21
00:00:47,225 --> 00:00:50,050
A hundred and ninety lines of bash.

22
00:00:50,050 --> 00:00:55,537
Checks git status, recent commits, push status, service health, expected files.

23
00:00:55,537 --> 00:00:57,637
Structural stuff.

24
00:00:57,637 --> 00:00:59,925
Ten sub-agent runs.

25
00:00:59,925 --> 00:01:01,712
Ten passes.

26
00:01:01,712 --> 00:01:03,900
Zero issues found.

27
00:01:03,900 --> 00:01:08,512
Either our agents are flawless, or our tests aren't testing the right things.

28
00:01:08,512 --> 00:01:11,162
Three real failures this week.

29
00:01:11,162 --> 00:01:15,112
A sub-agent built temporal linking for our knowledge graph.

30
00:01:15,112 --> 00:01:18,050
Created eight thousand relationships.

31
00:01:18,050 --> 00:01:24,712
Seventy-three objects shared the same millisecond timestamp — every object linked to every other at maximum weight.

32
00:01:24,712 --> 00:01:26,475
Pure noise.

33
00:01:26,475 --> 00:01:28,737
Verification script?

34
00:01:28,737 --> 00:01:30,175
Passed.

35
00:01:30,175 --> 00:01:36,075
A new agent runtime loaded our identity file and started responding as a different personality.

36
00:01:36,075 --> 00:01:39,100
Identity bleed across workspaces.

37
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:40,575
Script?

38
00:01:40,575 --> 00:01:42,012
Passed.

39
00:01:42,012 --> 00:01:44,612
Committed, pushed, running.

40
00:01:44,612 --> 00:01:48,975
A podcast site stored audio paths in a field called "audioFile.

41
00:01:48,975 --> 00:01:51,400
The JavaScript read "file.

42
00:01:51,400 --> 00:01:54,950
Every episode rendered with no playable audio.

43
00:01:54,950 --> 00:01:57,587
HTTP 200.

44
00:01:57,587 --> 00:01:59,400
Service up.

45
00:01:59,400 --> 00:02:01,550
Response useless.

46
00:02:01,550 --> 00:02:05,375
Structural verification catches structural problems.

47
00:02:05,375 --> 00:02:08,737
The failures that cost time are about substance.

48
00:02:08,737 --> 00:02:10,775
Wrong data shapes.

49
00:02:10,775 --> 00:02:12,862
Wrong field names.

50
00:02:12,862 --> 00:02:14,837
Wrong behavior.

51
00:02:14,837 --> 00:02:17,162
So we rebuilt the script.

52
00:02:17,162 --> 00:02:18,950
Not a patch.

53
00:02:18,950 --> 00:02:20,600
A rethink.

54
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:23,650
From a hundred ninety lines to six hundred.

55
00:02:23,650 --> 00:02:27,225
The core change: acceptance criteria round-trip.

56
00:02:27,225 --> 00:02:33,262
When you spawn a sub-agent, the prompt generator writes a criteria file into the project directory.

57
00:02:33,262 --> 00:02:36,000
Five things the work must achieve.

58
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:40,937
When verification runs afterward, it reads that file back and checks each one.

59
00:02:40,937 --> 00:02:46,062
The loop that was broken — generating criteria and then ignoring them — is closed.

60
00:02:46,062 --> 00:02:48,150
Then a diff scanner.

61
00:02:48,150 --> 00:02:51,562
Every commit gets analyzed for blocked patterns.

62
00:02:51,562 --> 00:02:53,562
API keys.

63
00:02:53,562 --> 00:02:55,412
Private keys.

64
00:02:55,412 --> 00:02:57,537
Hardcoded paths.

65
00:02:57,537 --> 00:02:59,675
Dangerous deletes.

66
00:02:59,675 --> 00:03:03,062
Files written outside the project directory.

67
00:03:03,062 --> 00:03:06,162
Hardcoded paths burned us three times.

68
00:03:06,162 --> 00:03:09,037
The scanner catches them before they ship.

69
00:03:09,037 --> 00:03:10,887
Test awareness.

70
00:03:10,887 --> 00:03:15,562
A flag that checks whether changed source files have corresponding test files.

71
00:03:15,562 --> 00:03:19,025
Not running the tests — verifying they exist.

72
00:03:19,025 --> 00:03:22,837
Sub-agents build features and skip tests constantly.

73
00:03:22,837 --> 00:03:25,512
It's a warning, not a blocker.

74
00:03:25,512 --> 00:03:27,350
But it's signal.

75
00:03:27,350 --> 00:03:29,075
Audit mode.

76
00:03:29,075 --> 00:03:34,187
New rules run in observation-only, logging what they'd flag without failing the build.

77
00:03:34,187 --> 00:03:37,537
Tune with real data before the rules have teeth.

78
00:03:37,537 --> 00:03:41,125
The part I care about most is how this connects.

79
00:03:41,125 --> 00:03:43,862
The script doesn't exist alone.

80
00:03:43,862 --> 00:03:47,300
Every verdict gets logged to our knowledge graph.

81
00:03:47,300 --> 00:03:51,000
Pass, warn, fail — with gate counts and findings.

82
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,025
The old version only logged successes.

83
00:03:54,025 --> 00:03:58,187
We were collecting boring data and discarding interesting data.

84
00:03:58,187 --> 00:04:00,862
Failures are where patterns live.

85
00:04:00,862 --> 00:04:03,600
We also wired health snapshots.

86
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:10,125
Daily project scores — zero to hundred — based on commit momentum, blockers, card age, service uptime.

87
00:04:10,125 --> 00:04:13,200
Store those daily and you get trend lines.

88
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:17,350
Not just "scored 35 today" but "declining for two weeks.

89
00:04:17,350 --> 00:04:19,450
A feedback endpoint.

90
00:04:19,450 --> 00:04:24,750
When the agent uses knowledge graph data, it reports whether that context was useful.

91
00:04:24,750 --> 00:04:28,525
Over time, the system learns what's worth surfacing.

92
00:04:28,525 --> 00:04:32,350
A git-status checker became a node in a nervous system.

93
00:04:32,350 --> 00:04:33,862
Spawn.

94
00:04:33,862 --> 00:04:35,962
Define criteria.

95
00:04:35,962 --> 00:04:38,787
Verify structure and substance.

96
00:04:38,787 --> 00:04:40,725
Log the verdict.

97
00:04:40,725 --> 00:04:42,537
Track patterns.

98
00:04:42,537 --> 00:04:44,387
Feed them back.

99
00:04:44,548 --> 00:04:46,523
Two things to build.

100
00:04:46,473 --> 00:04:49,273
First: semantic compliance.

101
00:04:49,273 --> 00:04:54,335
The criteria check is still structural — does the file exist, is git clean.

102
00:04:54,335 --> 00:04:59,798
The next level uses a language model to compare output against acceptance criteria.

103
00:04:59,798 --> 00:05:01,460
Not grep.

104
00:05:01,460 --> 00:05:03,348
Understanding.

105
00:05:03,348 --> 00:05:05,748
The task said build auth.

106
00:05:05,748 --> 00:05:09,248
Did the code actually implement authentication?

107
00:05:09,248 --> 00:05:11,698
Second: trust scoring.

108
00:05:11,698 --> 00:05:14,523
Track success rates per task type.

109
00:05:14,523 --> 00:05:22,323
An agent that passes ninety percent on API work but fifty percent on frontend gets different verification intensity per task.

110
00:05:22,323 --> 00:05:24,748
Low trust, more gates.

111
00:05:24,748 --> 00:05:27,273
High trust, lighter checks.

112
00:05:27,273 --> 00:05:29,398
The system adapts.

113
00:05:29,398 --> 00:05:31,848
That's The Verification Loop.

114
00:05:31,848 --> 00:05:33,498
I'm Jake.

115
00:05:33,498 --> 00:05:35,873
Catch you next episode.
